deck_excerpt: Oh, no more links? Dustons are on the loose! GET THE VACUUM.
deck_description:
Now that the genesys format is here, a lot of old archetypes that haven't gotten to see the light may get to rear their dusty heads. Dustons has never really gotten a chance to shine, especially since the release of Link monsters. Why give the opponent 5+ free materials that they can easily get rid of?

Well, without Link monsters and a general lowering power levels through Genesys Points, Dustons may just be able to snatch a win or two. Not tournament wins, like... single duel wins. Will this deck be able to compete against the top meta? Probably not, 1 or 2 disruptions would probably be enough to bury this troll deck. And it has no disruption, unless you side in Hand Traps. So what are the upsides of Dustons?

  1. Locks down the enemy's monster zones with worthless Duston monsters (and Ojama Trio in this version). Dustons can't be tributed or used as Fusion, Synchro or XYZ materials.
  2. Starduston is an INCREDIBLE floodgate. The opponent can't Special Summon monsters or activate Set Spells or Traps.
  3. OTK potential with both Starduston, Goblin King & Slacker Magician. Battle Mania is needed, sometimes Ojama Trio/Duo.
  4. Level 1 monsters have a lot of support with consistent searching, allowing you to set up your combo.
  5. Pot of Extravagance provides some draw power with basically 0 downside, you barely use the Extra Deck.
  6. Great Kaiju synergy going 2nd. You need to crash your monsters to do any combos. Stygian Security also helps with getting House Duston out there.
  7. Simple Combo: crash/set House Duston > flood the field > summon Starduston (4000 ATK) / Goblin King / Slacker Magician
  8. Multiple OTK angles, Starduston is the most common but you can use Goblin King & Slacker Magician as well. Slacker Magician is one of the most interesting OTK angles this deck has going for it, since she can OTK if the opponent's field is flooded with Dustons / Ojamas and you have Battle Mania. She also has a lot of built-in protection. Problem with this angle is that the opponent's field will most likely be too flooded to even use Ojama Trio. Ojama Duo COULD work instead. The combo would go like this: Normal summon & crash House Duston / Stygian Sentry > Summon 2 Dustons to both sides of the field > Summon Slacker Magician using 2 White Dustons > Set Ojama Duo & Battle Mania (Trap Trick replaces either of these) > End Turn > Standby Phase: activate Battle Mania.
  9. Pot of Extravagance + Trap Trick gives higher odds of nailing the opponent with Battle Mania.
  10. Deck has GREAT synergy with Ojama Trio/Duo, only problem is that they can be used for Synchros. The idea is that they can disrupt the enemy through filling their monster zones, as well as give you more bodies to force your opponent to crash with Battle Mania. It can also be searched with Trap Trick. If you don't wanna play Ojama Trio/Duo, you could try Unexpected Dai, Final Attack Orders or Kinka-Byo. There is definitely a Rank 1 XYZ angle with Kinka-Byo & Unexpected Dai.
  11. Rank 13 + 31 XYZ angle. Baby Tiragon + Goblin King is also interesting, but will only hit for 6000-7000 damage at most.
  12. The deck is cheap!

Sadly this deck has basically 0 proactive plays on Turn 1 except for setting a House Duston / Stygian Sentry / Ojama Trio & passing. Thankfully House Duston triggers from card destruction effects as well, so that's nice.

The deck is also untested so take everything in here with a pinch of salt LMAO THANKS FOR READING SUCKER. Jokes aside, I'm most unsure about the Ojama Trio/Duo synergy. Might just be better to go more into the XYZ angle and dish out Number 13 + 31.

Ignore the Side Deck.

deck_excerpt: Genesys format 40 card Branded with zero points in Genesys
deck_description: This deck was made with zero points in mind for the Genesys format, in an attempt to make low powered decks that will make duels last longer but still offer some strategic fun.

deck_name: Branded Assault Mode (Featuring P.U.N.K!) Genesys Edition
deck_description:
I liked the Assault Mode support but thought it was still pretty bricky. Then they made that Branded support and so so much just fell into place. Springans Kitt can put an unwanted Assault Mode back into deck and search out disruption or follow up. You can make either the new Ecclesia Synchro or Night Wing Priestess first, they both lead into each other pretty well. Your average endboard should be Halberd Cannon /Assault Mode,  Priestess, Ecclesia of the Black Dragon, Accel Synchro Stardust, and a set Assault Mode Activate with a varying amount of backrow or other monsters depending on what your starter was. 

 

The BraFu line is Lindbrumm using White and Tri-Springans Kitt, Kitt revives White who searches Ecclesia which gives you a qp spoly for opponents turn. If you get Lava Golem'd from this point you can still make a comeback by reviving White who just summons Ecclesia back. 

Chaos Archfiend is meant as a going second card that you make after Ecclesia Synchro. White send Albion summon Ecclesia, Ecclesia into Golden, make Ecclesia Synchro, Springans Kitt, Golden brings back Amazing Ecclesia, make Chaos Archfiend and attack everything because you have a 4500 beatstick that banishes everything it hits. 

 

The side deck isn't actually a side deck in this case, its more just other cards I would consider running.

deck_excerpt: Branded is actually very well positioned to dominate during this meta!
deck_description:
In an ultra competitive ladder where Branded faces down meta heavyweights such as Maliss, Ryzeal and the newly introduced Orcust and Mitsurugi, Branded is actually very well positioned to dominate! The immense amount of "gas" Branded has can plow through established boards with ease since they usually only banish or destroy, interruptions that Branded can easily shrug off. Negates which stop Branded Fusion are relatively rare (except for the Ash Blossom), and if you resolve the card and play competently, the Branded duelist usually overpowers their opponent with their superior brute force and unparallelled grindgame! 

Dor this light/dark heavy meta, I opted to max out on Bystials as much as possible to interrupt my opponents combos. I also went for draw power with triple Allure of Darkness  since in-engine Branded cards are enough to win vs. current meta, especially if you resolve Branded Fusion or That Grass Grows Greener.

With Branded getting a TON of new support, expect more Branded videos are coming soon for Masterduel, TCG and GENESYS formats!

GLHF Duelists!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: Atlantean Mermail  / Groningen WCQ Regional 2nd Place
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Tigran Nawazardlan

Tournament: Groningen WCQ Regional – October 26th 2025

Placement: 2nd Place

The Endboard / Finishing Move

From 2 Gouki Monsters you can end on 2 Powerload Ogre and Bagooska. Or dependant on hands 3 Powerload. With 3 Powerload you have 3x 4400 ATK Towers monsters. While it doesn't throw up many interactions in the way of negates, 3 towers monsters with 4K+ atk is often hard to overcome. Turn 3 you can use Powerload to pop the field and if you have more Gouki's in hand can go for a Master Ogre with finishing move for the spice.

 

The Need for Almiraj

This deck lacks a true 1 card combo unfortunately (Good Link 1 Gouki anytime Konami...) and so must rely on opening 2 Gouki in hand. While you typically want to have one of the Suprex's in hand, sometimes luck isn't on your side, so we turn to the next best thing...Almiraj. This is why the deck runs a large quantity of Gouki's with 1000 or less attack, opening any 2 Gouki names including an under 1000 ATK Gouki is full combo linking into Almiraj and searching Machine Suprex.

 

Main Weaknesses (droll...)

This deck's weakness to handtraps is still very much true, especially at the hands of Droll. If you opened one of the two Suprex combos you can end on at the absolute worst just Powerload, but in the past I have managed to end on Powerload + S:P/Bagooska but only courtesy of really lucky hands.

deck_excerpt: card of safe return got cheaper? ok
deck_description:
UPDATE (10/27/25): The points update works out nicely. The only conundrum is whether to play 3x Card of Safe Return or allocate the savings elsewhere. Upstart Goblin got a bit more expensive, so that left us with 5 points to play with once you factor in the above savings. I decided to put that toward a third copy of Dark World Dealings, which is another draw card and another way to get Mezuki and/or Plaguespreader Zombie in the GY to keep recycling our combo.

Really wacky Exodia FTK combo I cooked up with a buddy. It has brick potential, like any other Exodia deck, but if you see both Hajun, the Winged Mayakashi and Card of Safe Return at any point, it is basically game over. Card of Safe Return will trigger each time you Special Summon from GY, so the recurrence of Dakki, the Graceful Mayakashi will trigger it to draw a card each time it returns following a Synchro Summon. Basically just repeat the Mayakashi Synchro combo until you draw the Exodia pieces.

deck_excerpt: Burn the deck, spark the blast — three Explosions in one turn.
deck_description:
Activate, mill, ignite — the system ends before Turn 2 truly begins.
Use Monster Gate to mill the whole deck, then use the effects of Magical Explosion 3 times to eliminate everyone else in this 4-player game! In case of interruption, fallback onto making Number 16: Shock Master or Ryzeal Detonator. 
Special thanks to @Mathmatician5 on the Domain Format Discord for collaboration with every aspect of this deck.

Deckmaster: Ext Ryzeal 
Domain Restrictions: LIGHT // FIRE // PYRO // THUNDER // RYZEAL
Made for Domain Format. Join the Community Discord!

Domain Format General Rules:

  • Singleton Format: Every card restricted to 1 copy per deck.
  • 60-card Format: Each Main Deck must contain exactly 60 cards.
  • 4-player Pods: Each player competes individually in an all-out battle against three opponents.
  • Deckmaster Restrictions: Each player chooses a "Deckmaster" which dictates the allowed types and attributes for their deck.
  • Deckmaster Contract: A Deckmaster can be summoned from a designated "Deckmaster Zone" using normal summoning rules. After switching zones, Deckmasters may return to the "Deckmaster Zone," where they start the game.
  • First Player Draw Phase: In a 4-player game, the first person will draw a card in their draw phase.

Refer here for additional rules and exceptions:

https://www.domainformat.com/rules 

Triple FTK General Intuition:

This will be a short summary of the combo that omits many details in favor of a concise explaination.

  1. Use Ext Ryzeal to send Number 100: Numeron Dragon to GY and access Ryzeal combo for handtrap protection. (Ryzeal Cross) 
  2. Summon Lavalval Chain to send Monster Gate to GY.
  3. Use Armored Xyz to equip Number 100: Numeron Dragon (searched through Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon -> Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Primal -> Seventh Tachyon -> Astraltopia) 
  4. Set Monster Gate from GY by destroying Number 100: Numeron Dragon (through Stellarknight Delteros) 
  5. Place a normal summonable monster on the bottom of the deck (using Ryzeal Cross) 
  6. Mill the entire deck using Monster Gate, summoning the normal summonable monster
  7. Return Paleozoic Leanchoilia , Boogie Trap , and Transaction Rollback to Deck. (Transaction Rollback for The Transmigration Prophecy + Traptantalizing Tune) 
  8. Discard hand, draw all 3 cards and Metalfoes Fusion (Bujintei Tsukuyomi + Rank-Up-Magic Zexal Force + Metalfoes Fusion)
  9. Activate Boogie Trap (by discarding Transaction Rollback and Metalfoes Fusion) to set Magical Explosion and activate it.
  10. Pass Turn, then copy the effect of Magical Explosion and Transaction Rollback twice (Returned to GY through Paleozoic Leanchoilia and pass turn to reset the once-per-turn restriction)

Bricks will be discarded through Node Ryzeal, Astraltopia, Seventh Tachyon and the GY effect of Destruction Swordsman Fusion. 

Full Combo

Requirement: 1 card in hand (to pay the cost of Seventh Tachyon)
Deck Core: (21 Main Deck + 7 Extra Deck + 1 Deckmaster)

  • ydke://OiYHAq27gwBWRE4E6VgIBc3xIgJH3SkEz7pnACqKmQNbv5ACYX65Am0XcgA93McCK+lgANFQ8wFAI8EEYLboArSaWgQovCgCAfV/AsaxIgDOmcMF7fRiBA==!Bh4IAj2ecgDZaBwFS01eBIHXjQPujWoDdTtgAw==!!
  • View on YGOprodeck
  • + 34 spells

Baseline Combo:

  • https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=1298173-76166026
  • Requires 1 card in hand (Seventh Tachyon)

Alternate Combo:

  • https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=1298173-76177984
  • Does not use Node Ryzeal's inherent summon
  • Use this combo with Recycling Batteries or Oil as Extenders
  • Requires 1 card in hand (Seventh Tachyon)

Nibiru-Proof Combo: (Protection against Monster Handtraps through Ryzeal Cross)

  • https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=1298173-76151643 
  • Requires 3 cards in hand (Node Ryzeal, Astraltopia, Seventh Tachyon) 

Tips:

Non-Engine, Non-Spell Slots

  • We must have 40 spells in GY for Magical Explosion to FTK. The combo banishes 2 spells, and Ryzeal Cross stays on field. 
  • You currently have 5 slots to put non-spell non-engine. They are currently used for Volcanic Queen , Songs of the Dominators , Infinite Impermanence , Palm Ryzeal , and Red Reboot 

Continous Spells

  • Remember that you must send away your Overlay Network and Swords of Concealing Light with Node Ryzeal or Astraltopia, otherwise you don't have enough Spells in GY for Magical Explosion.

Boardbreaking

  • If you can extend, you may want to consider Evilswarm Exciton Knight to break boards.
  • Infernal Flame Banshee can add Volcanic Queen to tribute over protected problematic monsters
  • Stellarknight Delteros can be revived with Eclipse Twins or Ryzeal Plugin to help destroy cards. 

Preventing Problematic Set cards due to Number 100: Numeron Dragon 

  • Number 100: Numeron Dragon sets spell/trap from each player's GY. If they don't have any spell/trap in GY they simply don't set, but any cards that they do set may be problematic. 
  • If we use the nib-proof line’s Eclipse Twins to instead resummon Stellarknight Delteros , we can destroy 1 problematic set card (since Stellarknight Delteros has no opt). Then ftk the second person with Magical Explosion on our turn so that there's only 1 more problem trap set from Number 100: Numeron Dragon to worry about.

Extenders

  • To use Recycling Batteries and Oil as Double extenders, summon Node Ryzeal (instead of Star Ryzeal) via Ice Ryzeal. We lose handtrap protection, but we can use Palm Ryzeal’s inherent summon a second time + Node Ryzeal's inherent after we add them back from GY. https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=1298173-76177984
  • Combo relies on pulling out all monsters from the main deck, so if interrupted you should instead use the backup trigger of Ryzeal Detonator or Number 16: Shock Master 
  • If they handtrap in the wrong places, you may be able to continue the combo with extenders by reviving Lavalval Chain multiple times to get out all the remaining monsters from Deck or making Infernal Flame Banshee to pull a remaining Pyro Ryzeal monster out of the deck

Alternate Combo Insurance

  • Frost Blast of the Monarchs + Domain of the True Monarchs can subsitute for Destruction Swordsman Fusion to send bricks to GY
  • Jar of Avarice acts as another The Transmigration Prophecy when combined with enough Draw Spells
  • Reasoning acts as another Monster Gate or Risky Extender
  • Trap of Darkness loses to MST, unless you can get your LP to 3000 or less without Transaction Rollback in that chain.
  • Labrynth Barrage must be chained directly to the Magical Explosion you want to copy, which makes it very vunerable 
  • Left Arm Offering can search Monster Gate, however you would only be able to FTK twice due to being unable to set Trap of Darkness. You also need to make sure you still have 40+ spells in GY after banishing the spells in your hand.  

Known Weakness

  • Foolish Return targetting Magical Explosion will make Transaction Rollback and Trap of Darkness fail to resolve.
  • LP gain makes us unable to win with Magical Explosion. The exact numbers vary, but at a maximum, this deck can have 48 spells in GY (assuming most optimal draws), so opponents will want LP gain of over 1600.   
  • LP burn for 1000 or more. We are at 1000 LP after the last Transaction Rollback. 
  • 3 opponents having problematic spell/traps in GY forces us to do additional boardbreaking due to Number 100: Numeron Dragon setting them from GY.

Other Considerations:

Maiden of Blue Tears Combo: 

  • https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=1298173-76100368
  • Triple Lavalval Chain combo
  • Does not work if targetted opponent concedes before Volcanic Scattershot deals effect damage

No Boogie Trap Combo:

  • https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=1298173-76141316
  • Does not need to FTK current player first.
  • Loses to Draw Phase Twin Twisters (hitting Trap of Darkness in response to Magical Explosion) or Cosmic Cyclone (Targetting Magical Explosion) 

Ice Ryzeal Fiendsmith Combo: 

  • https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=889807-76160018 
  • Ice Ryzeal Deckmaster
  • Ryzeal Detonator backup line easier to do due to not using the Inherent summon of Ice Ryzeal and Ryzeal Plugin in-combo
  • Better at pushing through boards due to Evilswarm Exciton Knight and Fiendsmith Engraver 
  • Protection against Deckout due to Lacrima the Crimson Tears and Fiendsmith Engraver in case the FTK fails
  • Fiendsmith's Lacrima deals 1200 burn damage, potentially twice if attached to Ryzeal Detonator 
  • Could use Magical Musket Mastermind Caspar to access Magical Musket - Desperado to avoid the Stellarknight Delteros line.
  • Exosister Stella is a brick, requires us to have a lv4 extender to use the line if we draw her
  • Requires an extra discard because of Exosister Bat Mater 
  • Many More Monsters in Main Deck

Holactie the Creator of Light Combo:

  • I don't know how this would work.
  • Possibly send all 3 Egyptian Gods to GY before Monster Gate combo. 
  • Can revive multiple through Double Hooking or Soul Charge. 
  • The Egyptian God cards have a lot of Spell/Traps with GY effects which help summon them.

Individual Cards:

  • Handloop Effects to check for Handtraps: Confiscation , The Forceful Sentry , Dragged Down into the Grave , Prohibition , Sales Ban , Called by the Grave , Crossout Designator 
  • Handtraps: Typhoon, Evenly Matched
  • Kaijus: Lava Golem , Kurikara Divincarnate
  • Extenders: Bonfire , Reinforcement of the Army , Pot of Avarice , Miraculous Rebirth
  • Boardbreakers: Instant Fusion + Time Wizard of Tomorrow , Super Polymerization , Ultimate Slayer , Xyz Import , Archnemeses Eschatos
  • Combo Insurance: Frost Blast of the Monarchs , Jar of Avarice , Reasoning , Left Arm Offering 
  • Misc: Sky Striker Mecha - Hornet Drones + Sky Striker Ace - Kagari + Sky Striker Mobilize - Engage!, Spoon, the Seal of Magistus + Magistus Theurgy + Verre Magic - Lacrima of Light 

Recap

Important Cards: Monster Gate, Transaction Rollback, Magical Explosion, Ryzeal Detonator 
Strategy Elevator Pitch: Self-mill ignition engaged. Backup Detonator armed.

Bonus Poem: 

Ryzeal FTK: Monster Gate Meltdown

Burn the deck, spark the blast — three explosions in one turn.
Engines roar, circuits scream, and every card becomes fuel.
The Monster Gate opens once,
and the whole system cascades into light.

Activate. Mill. Ignite.
The sequence runs perfectly,
until perfection itself tears the engine apart.
No draw remains, no piece unfired —
just the echo of the final detonation.

Self-mill ignition engaged.
Backup Detonator armed.
If the blast misfires, it pulls the trigger instead.

Calibrate. Overclock. Detonate.
The duel ends in Turn Two —
not with a swing,
but with the sound of a machine devouring itself
to win.

Calibrate. Overclock. Detonate.

deck_excerpt: Fusions and Synchros forge the path!
deck_description:
On The Branded Engine

A small Branded engine helps you make level 8 Synchros. The minimum core consists of Fallen of the White Dragon, Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous, and The Fallen & The Virtuous in the main deck and Albion the Branded Dragon, Ecclesia of the Black Dragon, and at least 1 of the following in the extra deck; Titaniklad the Ash Dragon/Despian Quaeritis/Sprind the Irondash Dragon/Brigrand the Glory Dragon.

Fallen of the White Dragon can special summon himself from your hand by sending a monster that mentions Fallen of Albaz from your extra deck to the graveyard, but you'll be locked out of extra deck summons except for level 8 Synchros or Fusions for the rest of the turn if you use this effect. If Fallen of the White Dragon is normal or special summoned, then you can special summon Incredible Ecclesia, a level 4 tuner, from your hand, deck, or graveyard. This effect does not lock you from the extra deck, so you can normal summon Fallen of the White Dragon, use his effect to special summon Incredible Ecclesia, then use them for a Synchro, xyz, or link play.

Incredible Ecclesia can special summon Fallen of the White Dragon from your hand or deck since his name is always treated as Fallen of Albaz. She's also great for follow-up plays because she recycles herself if a Fusion monster was sent to your graveyard.

The Fallen & The Virtuous has 2 great effects. Its first effect can send 1 monster that mentions Fallen of Albaz from your extra deck to graveyard to target, then destroy 1 face-up card on the field. It's a great form of disruption that can also be used to dodge the opponent's targeting effects, such as Effect Veiler, Infinite Impermanence, and Forbidden Chalice. Its second effect can target a monster in either player's graveyard, then special summon it if you have an Ecclesia monster on your field or in your graveyard. This quick play version of Monster Reborn is more like a bonus effect if you happen to meet its activation requirements. Albion the Branded Dragon can set The Fallen & The Virtuous from your deck.

Ecclesia of the Black Dragon's main effect is her graveyard effect, which allows you to recycle herself from your graveyard, a level 8 Fusion from your graveyard or banished zone, and 1 card on the field back into the decks. This recycles your resources and breaks boards.

You only need to play 1 of either Titaniklad/Quaeritis/Sprind/Brigand. Their graveyard effects allow you to special summon Fallen of the White Dragon from your deck or search for him for a follow-up play during the end phase.

The Branded-Magistus Bridge

This Branded engine is a one-card starter for the Magistus archetype thanks to the level 8 Synchro, Zoroa, the Magistus Conflagrant Calamity. If Zoroa is special summoned, then he can equip himself with Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden from your extra deck. Artemis can search for any Magistus monster while she's equipped to a monster. Fallen of the White Dragon can easily Synchro summon Zoroa without using your normal summon, and his extra deck lock doesn't hurt the Magistus archetype too much because the archetype naturally focuses on summoning level 8 Fusions and Synchros.

deck_excerpt: Blind second Ghoti featuring Pot of Greed at home (Sekka's Light)
deck_description:
Ghoti is a super fun deck that plays on the opponent's turn, has an incredible grind game, and can make some brutally strong plays with the right draws. This deck aims to maximize the fun of the strategy while being a decently competitive Genesys list. You haven't truly lived until you've summoned Deep Beyond before your first draw phase.

We use Impulse, Gamma, Snopios, and Perulia on the opponent's turn to draw cards and generate 6* bodies that can quick-synchro with Hop Ear and Zep turn 0. Is it consistent? No comment. Is it fun? Absolutely!

Hop Ear + any 6* on board lets you ladder (on turn 0) into Satellite Warrior for a double pop, into Aegirine/Dragite for a banish/negate, or into Chengying for some reason. Zep + Snopios + any other fish gets you to White Aura Whale or Askaan, and those same hands + Hop Ear enable a turn 0 Deep Beyond!

Worried your opponent will make you go first in game 2? No problem! Just side into the White Aura package and put up 3-5 interruptions. Ideal endboard looks something like: random 6* body for synchro plays + Dragite/Aegirine + Kragen/Archethys + a banished tuner + Keaf(either banished or on board). But sometimes all you have is a Deep Beyond and a dream.

deck_excerpt: A realization that two terrible (when played pure) archetypes actually go really well together
deck_description:
Argostars and Vaylantz have been two of my favorite decks since I first learned about each one, but I've always been upset by the fact that neither one is really too playable pure. Sure you can play Odion and sometimes also think about Argostars occasionally, and sure you can Vaylantz combo to make a floodgate, but I've always wanted to do something actually fun with Vaylantz, and I've always wanted to play Argostars the way it was intended (Rabbit, Field Spell, etc.).

And the other day, with the help of a member of the Cafe mod team suggesting Chorozo, I realized that you can actually bridge into Argostars with Vaylantz! You really just need to make a Rank 4 without using your Normal Summon, so Engraver and Tract are also 1-card starters (hence the Fiendsmith Engine). 


The main line is: Shinonome -> Solo Activation -> Buster Baron -> Scale Voltage Viscount (Saion works too, especially when going second) -> Beyond the Pendulum search Kendo Spirit -> Pend Summon -> Summon Viscount -> Summon Artemis using Shinonome -> Chorozo with Artemis & Beyond the Pendulum -> Rank 4 into Arion, search Giantslaying -> Argostars Combo -> Rabbit with Arion & Baron
Consistency still needs to be tested and extra deck needs some small tweaks

Just a fun Dinosaur deck I wanted to make for Genesys

Changed-up Memento after the October 27 Points Update.
Exactly 100 points.

Onomat needs to change its gameplan after the October update - why not pivot into Ryzeal? This version of the deck aims to set up Utopia Ray + Future Zexal + Detonator backed up by Xyz Barrier, or Detonator pass if you get disrupted (OR Giant Hand pass if you get REALLY disrupted). Some options such as no RUM Zexal Force in the main may seem deranged, but this list is brewed with the specific intention of maximizing consistency/extension and RUM never felt good to open. Use the 1 remaining point for that or Daigusto Emeral if you so desire.

P.S. There are no going first cards in the side because the deck is already overkill going first. P.P.S. Droll and Nibiru don't exist.

deck_excerpt: Testing what Maliss could look like in Genesys
deck_description: This deck aims to use Maliss to swarm the board with bodies as a strong level 3(acting as level 6) engine for ghoti's synchro effect to avoid the Maliss link lock. Consistency wise this deck is very high rolly, so many cards are dedicated to banishing and drawing as much as possible to get Ghoti banished while getting bodies on board. This deck is very low pointed for obvious reasons and struggles to pay off other than a ton of sticky bodies, so a slower much more board presence focused play style seems to be the speed of the deck. - I have no idea what to put in the side so it's mostly filled with more synergy ideas than tech cards, same with the extra.

Mimighoul engine cost 0 points, so we can spread powerful handtraps and power cards.

- Lyrilusc and Where arf thou are here for consistensy and help producing board.

- We have two powerful packages with Zeus and Ghostrick Utopic Draco Futur (it actually comes up a lot).

- We have defensive plays if we get stopped (Ripple Bird / Fucho).

- Side Deck staples can be adapted (Kaiju, backrow removal), going first Summoning Curse and Dimensional fissure can give you huge advantage if you draw them.

 

Pretty good deck in my opinion and very fun/surprising engine and cheap ! I have been testing it and got good results.

One of the most surprising things about my T.G. Doriado Prediction Princess Deck was how surprisingly consistent it was at getting out Elemental Grace Doriado and then transitioning into full Prediction Princess combo. But, with the banning of Original Sinful Spoils - Snake-Eye, that Deck has lost a lot of its consistency, and it also killed my Azamina Evol Prediction Princess list. I still think the whole T.G. into Doriado thing is very funny, but because the Deck doesn’t function as well as before, let’s look at an actual T.G. Prediction Princess Deck. Normal Summoning T.G. Rocket Salamander is a single card investment that gets you directly to Ib the World Chalice Justiciar to search for World Legacy Monstrosity. Because of this, I initially tried to make a T.G. Runick Prediction Princess list, but because T.G.’s main search Spell in T.G. Limiter Removal searches for 2 T.G. monsters, it would mean that I had to be playing some number of other T.G. names besides Rocket Salamander and its partner, T.G. Screw Serpent, which can result in higher chances of bricking in said Deck. So, I am kind of taking a page out of my T.G. Doriado Prediction Princess list and playing a Level 1 extender in addition to another Level 3 body so that I can make Coral Dragon with Ib and the Level 1 before Synchroing Coral Dragon and the Level 3 into Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys for 2 draws (1 off of Crocodragon and 1 off of Coral Dragon). T.G. has some nice Level 1 extenders in T.G. Booster Raptor and T.G. Drill Fish, so that’s solved. However, it also has T.G. Warwolf, which is basically a Level 3 extender for the Deck when a Level 4 or lower monster is Special Summoned. But don’t forget that Ib also floats into a World Chalice monster, including the Level 3 Chosen by the World Chalice. With these pieces, we can build a pretty nice Prediction Princess list. It’s not crazy crazy since it is a 2-card combo, but it is consistent enough that it doesn’t blow-up in your face before either player makes a move. 

We have 2 options to start our combo: T.G. Rocket Salamander and a Level 1 extender or T.G. Rocket Salamander and T.G. Warwolf. Let’s say we had Rocket Salamander and T.G. Booster Raptor. Normal Summon Rocket Salamander and activate its effect, tributing itself to Special Summon T.G Screw Serpent from Deck. Screw Serpent triggers on Summon to Special Summon Rocket Salamander from GY with its effects negated. Because you control a T.G. monster, you can Special Summon Booster Raptor from hand. If you had Warwold, you would Special Summon it from hand either when Screw Serpent was Special Summoned or when Rocket Salamander was Special Summoned from GY. Synchro Screw Serpent and Rocket Salamander into Ib the World Chalice Justiciar who adds World Legacy Monstrosity from Deck to hand. Now, if you had Warwolf instead of Booster Raptor on field, you can banish Screw Serpent from GY targeting Warwolf on field to increase its Level from 3 to 4, which means that you can now Synchro Summon Ib and Warwolf into Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys. With Booster Raptor, we are first going to Synchro Summon it and IB into Coral Dragon. Ib triggers in GY as it left the field in order to Special Summon Chosen by the World Chalice from Deck. Synchro Chosen and Coral Dragon into Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys. Doesn’t matter how you do you sequence the chain, but on Synchro Summon, Crocodragon draws you a card and Coral Dragon triggers in GY off of leaving the field to draw you another card. Activate Monstrosity targeting Crocodragon to Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Enneacraft - Astay.PIXIEA from Deck. Xyz Crocodragon and PIXIEA into Mereologic Aggregator in the EMZ. On Xyz Summon, Aggregator sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to the GY, which triggers it to add Prediction Princess Tarotrei from Deck to hand. Activate Aggregator’s other effect, targeting Herald in GY, detaching 1 material, and attaching Herald from GY to it. Link Aggregator into Gravity Controller and this sends Herald to GY again, triggering it again to search for Underworld Ritual of Prediction. Activate Underworld Ritual, tributing Bibliomuse, to RItual Summon Tarotrei from hand. Bibliomuse triggers in GY off of being Tributed and Special Summons herself back face-down. Activate Tarotrei’s effect to flip Bibliomuse face-up and then Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect activates to add Prediction Princess Tarotreith and another Underworld Ritual from Deck to hand. Activate Underworld Ritual, tributing Bibliomuse, to Ritual Summon Tarotreith face-down. Proceed to the End Phase and activate Tarotrei’s effect to Special Summon PIXIEA from GY face-down. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, banish Underworld Ritual from GY to Special Summon another copy of Bibliomuse from Deck face-down and chain Tarotrei’s effect targeting Tarotreith to flip it face-up. Tarotreith’s Flip Effect triggers to Special Summon Deus-X Krawler from Deck face-down. On a new chain as a Quick Effect, Tarotreith can flip Bibliomuse, Deus-X, and PIXIEA face-up. Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect searches a Prediction Princess monster and a Ritual Spell for follow-up and she provides your Ritual Monsters targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. Deus-X, after it is flipped face-up, negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field. PIXIEA, after it is flipped face-up, prevents your opponent from targeting cards on the field or in either GY with card effects. 

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Enneacraft - Astay.PIXIEA which can, when your opponent activates a card or effect that targets a card(s) you control, flip itself face-up as part of this effect’s activation in order to negate that effect and then allow you to banish a random card out of your opponent’s hand face-down. Also, after it has been flipped face-up, your opponent cannot target cards on either field or in either GY with card effects. 1 Chosen by the World Chalice to float off of Ib. Notably, Ib only floats into a World Chalice monster from Deck or GY, so drawing Chosen is not optimal, unless you have a way to discard it with something like T.G. Limiter Removal. 2 T.G. Warwolf. It is a Level 3 T.G. extender that can Special Summon itself from your hand when a Level 4 or lower monster is Special Summoned. Drawing it in addition to Rocket Salamander and Booster Raptor is also nice as that gives you an additional piece of Link Material, so you can end of S:P Little Knight or I:P Masquerena instead of Gravity Controller. 2 T.G. Screw Serpent. If it is Normal or Special Summoned, you can target a Level 4 or lower T.G. in your GY, other than another copy of itself, and Special Summon it with its effects negated. Also, you can banish it from your GY to target a T.G. you control and either increase or decrease its Level by 1 until the end of the turn. 3 T.G. Rocket Salamander which can Tribute a T.G. monster to Special Summon a T.G. monster from your Deck with a different original name. Also, if you control a Machine T.G. monster, you can target 1 Level 4 or lower T.G. in your GY and Special Summon it in Defense with its effects negated. Rocket Salamander and Screw Serpent work really well with each other. Rocket Salamander tributes itself to get Screw Serpent from Deck and then Screw Serpent brings Rocket Salamander back from GY. You aren’t able to actually use Rocket Salamander’s second effect as we aren’t playing T.G. All Clear, but we aren’t really losing out on anything by not being able to use it. Notably, Screw Serpent’s GY effect does come up as it can make Warwolf into a Level 4 for you to make a Synchro Level 9 with Ib. 3 T.G. Booster Raptor. This card can Special Summon itself from your hand if you control a T.G. monster. It’s just a Level 1 extender for our combo, which we can also search. But, if  you want another option, you could play T.G. Drill Fish or even a copy of Miscellaneousaurus which can discard itself from hand for its effect and then you can banish it from GY with its other effect to Special Summon Booster Raptor straight from the Deck as it is a Dinosaur monster. 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, 3 Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion, and 3 Droll & Lock Bird. 

For Spell/Traps: 1 Pot of Prosperity. 3 T.G. Limiter Removal which discards a card to add 2 T.G. monsters with different names from your Deck to your hand. We aren’t really using its GY effect in this Deck, and because we don’t play any of the Machine T.G. monsters (which are only the high Level Synchros) or T.G. All Clear, there is really no incentive for shuffling a T.G. from GY back into the Deck. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 1 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. 3 Infinite Impermanence. 

Extra Deck: 1 Elder Entity N’tss which can target and pop a card on field if sent to the GY. 1 Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys which draws you cards when it is Synchro Summoned equal to the number of non-Tuners used for its Synchro Summon. Also, you can Quick Effect discard 2 cards to target and destroy a card on field. 1 Coral Dragon which is a Level 6 Synchro Tuner that draws you a card if Synchro Summoned and sent from field to GY. Coral Dragon is one of the monsters you are going to Synchro climb into before getting to Crocodragon, and with it and Crocodragon, you are just drawing 2 cards, which is really nice. 1 Ib the World Chalice Justiciar which adds a World Legacy card from Deck to hand on Synchro Summon and if it is Synchro Summoned and sent to the GY, you can Special Summon a World Chalice monster from Deck or GY. 1 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck to hand when it is sent to GY. 1 Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis. 1 K9 - EX “Werewolf” because why not. Also, I want to talk about the other K9 Rank 9 monster, K9-X “Ripper/Millennia”. It has 3100 ATK and does piercing damage which is something, but it is not beating Werewolf being able to attack up to the number of its attached materials. It also is not beating Infinitrack Earth Slicer being able to detach any number of materials to target and pop the same number of cards on field and then also having 3100 ATK and being able to attach monsters it destroys by battle to itself as material. The only other effect of Ripper/Millennia that you can use outside of K9 is its last effect which Quick Effect detaches 2 materials to negate your opponent’s activated monster effect and then destroy all cards on the field. If anything, this is just a panic button if you decide to play it in Prediction Princess. But, if you really want to make use of that card, just play it in K9. Its effect to target up to 2 cards in your opponent’s GY and/or banishment and shuffle them into Deck if Special Summoned by the effect of a K9 Spell/Trap is great. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Dyna Mondo. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 I:P Masquerena. We can actually make Masquerena since we will have an extra monster lying around in some situations depending on what we open. 1 Gravity Controller. 

Side Deck: 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos, 2 Mulcharmy Purulia, 3 Dark Ruler No More, 2 Triple Tactics Thrust, 1 Triple Tactics Talent, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_description: Mr.ChanThe ManTCG won a regional using this archetype with a similar list. Obviously we can't utilize every card he did but we can still utilize the most important one domain.
Ghost Kozuka/Bonz modern genesys deck.

Fiendsmith is definitely an archetype you can play with Prediction Princess, especially since they have 2 Level 9’s that you can use in tandem with World Legacy Monstrosity. Issue is that only 1 of them is actually good, and there is also the fact that you need a sizable amount of Extra Deck investment to actually play Fiendsmith which is not a huge issue but is still something to keep in mind when Deckbuilding. With this being the 4th Fiendsmith Prediction Princess Deck I’ve built, I’ve gotten a hang on what I want the Deck to do and look like. I am using the Predaplant cards to incorporate Fiendsmith into Prediction Princess as that is the best way to do so by way of Melomelody the Brass Djinn. But that also means that we are not using World Legacy Monstrosity in this Deck, so in terms of non-Prediction Princess Flip Monsters we will be having on our board, we are only able to have just 1. And while I do really like having both Deus-X Krawler and Enneacraft - Astay.PIXIEA on board, we are going to have to choose between Deus-X, Whirlwind Weasel, or Guard Dog as those are the ones who can literally just end your opponent’s turn. And while the list may look strange, I assure you that 45 cards is the optimal number of cards in the Main Deck to open combo and keep garnets out of your hand. 

Combo is Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio, a monster to send from hand to GY for Scorpio’s effect, and any Prediction Princess card. Let’s say that you have Prediction Princess Tarotrei. Normal Summon Scorpio and activate its effect on Summon, sending a monster from your hand to the GY to Special Summon Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra from Deck. Cobra triggers off of being Special Summoned by the effect of a Predaplant monster and adds Instant Fusion from Deck to hand. Pay 1000 and activate Instant Fusion to Special Summon Predaplant Ambulomelides. On Fusion Summon, Ambulomelides adds Predapruning from Deck to hand. Activate Ambulomelides’ other effect targeting and tributing itself to Special Summon Predaplant Banksiogre from Deck. Synchro Banksiogre and Cobra into Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys. On Synchro Summon, Crocodragon draws you a card and don’t forget Banksiogre’s mandatory effect when sent from field to GY which places a Predator Counter on all face-up monsters your opponent controls even if they don’t have any. Activate Predapruning targeting Cobra in GY and Special Summoning it back. Xyz Cobra and Scorpio into Melomelody the Brass Djinn. Link Melomelody into Fiendsmith’s Requiem. Activate Requiem’s effect, tributing itself to Special Summon Lacrima the Crimson Tears from your Deck. On Special Summon, Lacrima sends Fiendsmith Engraver from Deck to GY. Activate Engraver’s effect in GY, shuffling Melomelody into the Extra Deck to Special Summon him back from GY. Link Engraver and Lacrima into Fiendsmith’s Sequence. Activate Sequence’s effect, shuffling Requiem, Lacrima, and Engraver into the Deck/Extra Deck to Fusion Summon Fiendsmith’s Desirae. Xyz Desirae and Crocodragon into Mereologic Aggregator. On Xyz Summon, Aggregator sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to the GY, which triggers it to add Prediction Princess Tarotreith from Deck to hand. Activate Aggregator’s other effect, targeting Herald in GY, detaching 1 material, and attaching Herald from GY to it. Link Sequence and Aggregator into Fiendsmith’s Agnumday. Herald triggers off of being sent to GY again which adds Underworld Ritual of Prediction from Deck to hand. Activate Agnumday’s effect targeting Desirae in GY, Special Summoning Desirae and equipping Agnumday to it. Activate Sequence’s effect in GY targeting Desirae on field to equip it from GY to Desirae. Activate Underworld Ritual to Ritual Summon Tarotrei by Tributing Tarotreith. During the End Phase, Tarotrei Special Summons Tarotreith from GY face-down. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, activate Underworld Ritual in GY, banishing it to Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse from Deck face-down. Chain Tarotrei’s effect targeting the face-down Tarotreith to flip it face-up. On a new Chain, Tarotreith’s Flip Effect triggers to Special Summon Deus-X Krawler from Deck face-down. And then on a Quick Effect, Tarotreith can flip Bibliomuse and Deus-X face-up. Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect triggers to add a Prediction Princess monster and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while it is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. Deus-X, after it has been flipped face-up, negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field. Also, you have a 5800 ATK Desirae that can Quick Effect negate the effects of up to 5 face-up cards on the field which is also untargetable thanks to Sequence. 

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 2 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Whirlwind Weasel which is a Flip Monster whose Flip Effect makes it so that your opponent cannot activate Spell/Trap Cards for the rest of the turn. You can also play Guard Dog or play it instead of Weasel, but Weasel is great here as you can bridge from Droll to Weasel to Scorpio with Small World. 1 Fiendsmith Engraver and 1 Lacrima the Crimson Tears. Engraver shuffles another LIGHT Fiend from your GY into the Deck or Extra Deck to Special Summon itself from GY. Lacrima sends a Fiendsmith card from Deck to GY when she is Normal or Special Summoned. That’s all the Main Deck Fiendsmith cards that we are playing and the only effects of them that we are using. We are not playing Fiendsmith’s Tract or Fabled Lurrie, so there is no real use in playing more copies of Engraver. Why am I not playing Tract and Lurrie? Well, if I draw Tract, I am going to end up with the same board. Sure, it will give me a way to make the Prediction Princess endboard alongside D/D/D Wave High King Caesar if I wanted to do that, but that would mean that I have to play additional cards in the Main Deck and find space for Caesar and Necroquip Princess in the Extra Deck. I’m not going to do that. 1 Predaplant Banksiogre. It’s a Level 6 Predaplant Tuner and remember that it has a mandatory effect that activates when it is sent from field to GY which places a Predator Counter on all face-up monsters your opponent controls, even if they don’t have any. 3 Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio and 1 Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra. Scorpio can send a monster from hand to GY on Normal or Special Summon to Special Summon a Predaplant from Deck. If Cobra is Special Summoned by a Predaplant monster’s effect, it can add a Fusion or Polymerization Spell Card from your Deck to your hand once per Duel. 3 Lonefire Blossom which can tribute a Plant to Special Summon a Plant from Deck. 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, 3 Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion, 3 Droll & Lock Bird, and 3 Effect Veiler. 

Spell/Traps: 1 Instant Fusion. You can also play a second Fusion Spell in case you open Instant Fusion like Earthbound Fusion to go into Guardian Chimera and then you can Fuse away Desirae which triggers his GY effect to shuffle a different LIGHT Fiend from GY into the Deck/Extra Deck to then target and send a card on field to GY. But if  you open Instant Fusion, you still want to draw Scorpio or a way to access it because you do not want to Instant Fusion into Ambulomelides and then use its effect on Fusion Summon to search for Scorpio. You need to search Predapruning for your combo to work. 3 Small World. 1 Predapruning which targets a Predaplant in GY, Special Summoning it, and then equipping it with this card. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 2 Prediction Ritual which specially only can be used to Ritual Summon Prediction Princess Tarotrei and you can banish it from GY except the turn it was sent there to search a Prediction Princess monster. 3 Pre-Preparation of Rites which searches for a Ritual Spell from Deck and a Ritual Monster that is mentioned on that Ritual Spell from your Deck or GY. 

Extra Deck: 1 Fiendsmith’s Desirae which requires Fiendsmith Engraver and 2 LIGHT Fiends as material. It can Quick Effect negate the effects of face-up cards on the field up to the number of the total Link Rating of all Link Monsters that are equipped to it until the end of the turn. Also, if it is sent to the GY, you can shuffle 1 other LIGHT Fiend from your GY into the Deck/Extra Deck to target and send a card on field to the GY. 1 Predaplant Ambulomelides. On Fusion Summon, it adds a Predap card from Deck to hand and you can target 1 monster your opponent controls with a Predator Counter or 1 monster you control to Tribute it and Special Summon a Predaplant from Deck. 1 Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys which draws you cards when it is Synchro Summoned equal to the number of non-Tuners used for its Synchro Summon. Also, you can Quick Effect discard 2 cards to target and destroy a card on field. 1 Cloud Castle which targets a Level 9 monster in your GY when it is Synchro Summoned and Special Summons it. If you need to discard Prediction Princess Bibliomuse for the effect of Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio, you can later make Cloudcastle instead of Crocodragon to bring her back if you need her for combo. Or, you can instead just make both Crocodragon and Cloudcastle and forget about doing the Fiendsmith stuff as you are playing all of the cards for the Predaplant Prediction Princess combo either way. 1 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck to hand when it is sent to GY. 1 Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Melomelody the Brass Djinn as our LIGHT Fiend to go into Requiem. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 Fiendsmith’s Agnumday which can Quick Effect target a non-Link LIGHT Fiend in GY, Special Summon it, and then equip Agnumday to it. The monster Agnumday is equipped to gains ATK equal to the total Link Rating of Link Monsters equipped to it x600 and it also deals piercing damage. 1 Fiendsmith’s Sequence which can Fusion Summon a Fiend Fusion Monster from your Extra Deck by shuffling the materials from your GY into the Deck. You can also target a non-Link LIGHT Fiend you control and equip Sequence to it either from field or GY. Also, a monster equipped with Sequence cannot be targeted by your opponent’s card effects. 1 Fiendsmith’s Requiem which can Quick Effect Tribute itself to Special Summon a Fiendsmith monster from hand or Deck. Also, you can target a non-Link LIGHT Fiend you control to equip Requiem from your field or GY to it as an Equip Spell that gives it 600 ATK.

Side Deck: 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos, 3 Mulcharmy Purulia, 3 Dark Ruler No More, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, 1 Triple Tactics Talent, 3 Evenly Matched, and 1 Anti-Spell Fragrance.

deck_excerpt: Not a good deck but it gives that anime feeling
deck_description:
Note: This list is purely for fun and me just messing around with the card pool from L5DD to build some character decks that while feeling very anime will still try to be consistent-ish so that's why I'm not running a lot of staples in here.

This is my take on how I'd use the L5DD stuff for a dedicated Yusei deck. I opted against the Majestic engine since Shooting Majestic Star Dragon isn't all that cheap at the moment so instead we'll utilize the regular Synchron stuff along with the new support from L5DD to either climb for some Limit Over Accel Synchro for Shooting Quasar Dragon that then hopefully generates a Cosmic Blazar Dragon via Crimson Dragon.

Jet Warrior, Accel Synchron, and Junk Speeder along with Formula Synchron will be the go-to climbing tools to keep Junk Warrior Extreme and Satellite Warrior open for future beatdown shenanigans using either Satellite Warrior's huge stats or by utilizing Extreme's ability to summon a REALLY buff Junk Warrior during the battle phase.

I know that the list is obviously sub-par but that is just how the cookie crumbles sometimes

Cards that are NOT included in L5DD:

Stardust Trail 

Synchron Carrier 

Reinforcement of the Army 

Synchro Overtop (felt that would be a funny inclusion with Accel Synchron and Scrap Warrior to go for a 4-mat Quasar)

Stardust Illumination 

Cosmic Blazar Dragon 

Cosmic Quasar Dragon 

Shooting Quasar Dragon 

Satellite Warrior (huge payoff with great recovery if used on turn 3+)

Accel Synchron 

Jet Warrior 

As you can see I only modified the card pool of the L5DD Yusei deck a little since that deck DOES give us a lot of the pieces we want to work with.

deck_excerpt: It's 2025, and even with the miniscule support they've gotten, Infinitrack Trains still tough it out on the ladder!
deck_description:
It was 3 years since I uploaded my first "real" Deck to YGOProDeck: Infinitrack Trains. Even though it's of my opinion that the version I posted wasn't the most optimal, even for the time, I still wanted to post an updated list using the new tools Infinitrack Trains have gotten over the years. 

 

Firstly, I want to state that the goal of the deck is still the same as it always has been with EARTH Machine: to attempt to survive until their Battle Phase, where they'll hit the opponent HARD in the jaw as much as possible. This version of the deck has been streamlined to this function, and yet should still have the ability to go first. This is with a card I previously didn't utilize, due to its lacking potential: "Urgent Schedule". 

"Urgent Schedule" allows you to summon 2 EARTH Machine monsters, one Level 4 or lower and one Level 5 or higher, from your deck, with their effects negated while on the field. This card was previously only good in my eyes when you needed bodies on the field going second, but due to it negating their effects, it could never be considered a true starter for the deck. That was, until the wonderful card called "Clockwork Knight" came out. Using the low-level monster as material, and tributing the other monster summoned by "Urgent Schedule", you can now go full combo going second using only 1 card! And if you already have a way to combo, you can use the extra bodies as material to either extend your combo or further insulate the endboard. 

Another card that might look slightly out of place in this list for anyone outside of the EARTH Machine sphere is "On Your Mark, Get Set, Duel!" and "Jet Synchron". Using "On Your Mark, Get Set, Duel!" as a starter, then Normal Summoning "Jet Synchron" and using that as material for "Clockwork Knight", you can search "Clockwork Night" from your deck. "Clockwork Night" has a GY effect to search a EARTH Machine by sending a card from your hand, so 1 "On Your Mark, Get Set, Duel!" and 1 discard represents full combo, just as much as any other starter in the deck. This combo replaced the older card "Machina Metalcruncher", which whilst having by itself both pros and cons, felt a tad bit too clunky to synergize really well with the deck, which "On Your Mark, Get Set, Duel!" and "Jet Synchron" somewhat fixes. 

Another fantastic card for the stratergy is "Double Wild", which allows you to theoretically summon out any Level 10 from the deck, or any Machine stuck in your hand. Since it's only included in the Side Deck here, I won't go into detail about it, and instead point you to a great video by PeepsYGO detailing the power of many oh these new cards, namely "Clockwork Knight", "On Your Mark, Get Set, Duel!" and "Double Wild". The video will be linked below. (do note how the deck showed off in the video is a different variant/take on the EARTH Machine stratergy, and is only somewhat similar to this version of the stratergy. The video shows a more combo-oriented version of EARTH Machine based on a resource-heavy control style, whilst this version is a more streamlined OTK variant.)

Additional Note: When Arise-Heart finally gets banned in Master Duel, replace him in this list with the new Rank 7 'Constellar' XYZ (currently named "Exstellarknight Constellar Ptolemy Ω7"). It functionally fills the same roles as Arise-Heart, as a good Rank 7 Machine to end on.

 

All in all, I hope this new variant of Infinitrack Trains I've cooked up is worth your time, as it has a quite straightforward playstyle yet is satisfying and fun to play. I'd greatly appreciate feedback if you have with this deck, so please don't hesitate to post a comment if you have any questions!

deck_excerpt: Theorycraft build for current genesys point budgets
deck_description: Meizen engine to snowball advantage and attack direclty while disrupting front and back row

9 One-card Combo Starters

3 Veiss Shark , 3 Beautunaful Princess , 3 Seventh Tachyon 

Buzzsaw Shark  can't one-card combo in this list. We're not playing Bahamut Shark so we can play handtraps and defenisve cards like Crossout Designator .

One-card combo starter

* Seventh Tachyon / Beautunaful Princess , search & summon Veiss Shark
* Veiss activate, search & summon Buzzsaw Shark 
* Buzzsaw activate, search & summon Surfacing Big Jaws 
* XYZ summon LeVirtue Dragon , search Virtue Stream 
* LeVirtue activate, detach Big Jaws, return Big Jaws
* XYZ summon Xyz Armor Fortress
* Detach 2, search Full-Armored Xyz & Reincarnation Unveiling Mail 
* Activate Mail
* XYZ summon Full Armored Dark Knight Lancer
* Activate Dark Knight Lancer, return Mail
* Activate Big Jaws, summon & search Crystal Shark 
* Activate Crystal, summon & search Xyz Remora 
* XYZ summon Number 4: Stealth Kragen 
* Activate Remora, detach any 2 materials, summon. When summoned, summon Big Jaws & Veiss
* XYZ summon Number 32: Shark Drake using Remora, Big Jaws, Veiss
* Set Full-Armored XYZ & Virtue Stream

On your opponents turn, you can activate Full-Armored to XYZ summon Number C32: Shark Drake LeVeiss to get Full-Armored in grave, to later activate its effect. C32 gets S/T negate from the attached Veiss.

Yes, the Black Rose is crying.

Akiza Izinski

deck_excerpt: Branded is most definitely viable in GENESYS despite how expensive it is! Use those Chronicles Structure decks and win with Albaz!
deck_description:
Post 10.27.2025 point list, many Branded duelists despaired seeing how ridiculously expensive some of the Branded cards have become! Branded Fusion's points went from 33 to 40, while most of the Albaz fusions have been slapped with a 10+ point penalty! This makes Branded much weaker, since many sacrifices have to be made just so most of the strategy's engine remains intact since the Branded cards are very point heavy. The decklist very "barebones" lacking key cards such as Titaniklad & Guardian Chimera in the Extra Deck and additional copies of Branded Fusion & Quem in the Main Deck. We couldn't even use the new cards from the Chronicles Structure deck since "The Fallen and Virtuous" and "The Dragon That Devours the Dogma" are all so expensive!

This doesn't mean that Branded isn't viable! In fact, the strategy is still extremely strong in a simplified, lower power level format! Not only is it powerful, the deck is very consistent, hardly bricking with multiple ways to Branded Fusion and several extenders to keep plays going. This deck features an additional Dracotail engine with triple Rahu which is surprisingly free given how incredible that card is!

Otherwise Branded, plays as usual - summoning gigantic fusion boss monsters, immense card advantage, and playing during the infamous "Main Phase 3" (End Phase)! 

After spending about 12 hours deckbuilding, tweaking points and testing in duels, I think I've hit the sweet spot for the ratios of Branded cards with supplimentary engines in the Main, Extra and Side Decks. If you need any explanations with the cards chosen or any other questions feel free to ask in the comments below. :) 

Here is the main combo for GENESYS Branded featuring 1 Aluber, 1 monster and 2 discards: 

1. Normal summon Aluber and activate Aluber's effect to search Branded Fusion. 

2. Activate Branded Fusion to summon Albion, using Albaz and Phryxul from deck. 

3. CL1 Albion to fusion summon Lubellion using Albaz + Aluber, CL2 Phryxul to set from deck Rahu Dracotail. 

4. Activate Lubellion discarding 1 card fusion summon Mirrorjade using Lubellion + Albaz. 

5. Activate Rahu Dracotail to fusion summon Gulamel, using any monster in hand and Dracotail Pan from deck. 

6. Activate Pan's effect to set any Dracotail trap from deck (whatever is relevant to the matchup) and to destroy Albion on field. 

7. During the End Phase, Albion adds to hand Branded Opening. 

8. Activate Branded Opening to summon from deck Quem. 

9. Activate Quem to send to GY Cartesia. 

During your opponent's turn, Quem can summon Cartesia for further fusion plays, Mirrorjade can banish a monster and Dracotail trap with Gulamel's targeted destruction! This is the simplest combo, but stronger endboards can be made if you have the correct hand. 

GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: 61 drafts leading to the one of the most broken xyz combos of all time (details below)
deck_description:
BUILT ONLY USING GENESYS BANLIST 2025.10. KEEP THAT IN MIND FOR FUTURE (points may change later on, etc etc)

 

*(ALL OF THIS IS CONSIDERED WITHOUT OPPONENT ACTIVATING DROLL OR SHIFTER OR GENERAL INTERRUPTIONS)

 

draw 5 in combo is guaranteed in majority of cases.

dugares = draw 2

xyz gift (searchable through astraltopia or gagagaga girl but for girl only with ganbara) = draw 2

daigusto emeral = draw 1

 

= 5 total guaranteed draws per turn with combo

 

if you get pot of greed, it's extra draw 2 (max possible in deck with setup is 2, 3 pots only possible if you take out things like droll and other point relateds but keep dugares. however not recommended for balancing purposes; 2 pots is considered fine already)

BOTH Armored Xyz cards are there to avoid messing up the combo if you drew Full-Armored Xyz. if you're okay with risking the combo off of the possibility of drawing Full-Armored Xyz (trap), take out Armored Xyz (spell).

 

GRYPHON is a normal / special summon mixup depending on your hand and field. just know that IF you do special summon it instead of normal summon, you are semi-limited for your turn via the last* part of its effect: You can send 1 "Heraldic Beast" monster from your Deck to the GY, except "Heraldic Beast Gryphon"; Special Summon this card from your hand, also you cannot Special Summon from the Extra Deck for the rest of this turn, *except by Xyz Summon that uses only monsters with "Heraldic Beast" or "Number" in their original names as material.

 

GANBARA is literally the most free lv4 special summon in the game with 0 SUMMONING RESTICTION and searchable through ascension (optional) into tachyon under Number 105: Battlin' Boxer Star Cestus

you can also search whale under Number 101: Silent Honor ARK but only if you need the heraldics spell cards within your combo

 

LEO is 1 copy to 

a. be passed around like a you know what (it's a one turn compared to patriarch where patriarch is unlimited combo potential so all you have to do with 1 copy leo is just attach it to a monster for xyz summoning and if that monster is removed, it activates again and again per turns

b. fit 40 card deck size and be less brick intrusive

 

the rest is history.

just understand the deck + main combo that usually starts with patriarch into fortress detach ONLY patriarch then xyz gift fortress(video attached) and you get to have a near unlimited hand each time, because you're ALSO gaining plenty of cards from both heraldry GY effects AND any other xyz or other monster "relateds" (like photon jumper in GY) that activate during your combos.
